n repeated in a six-panel layout, divided by thin white lines. Each panel shows the same Topol tube applying toothpaste to a toothbrush, with day labels in white text: “Monday,” “Tuesday,” “Wednesday,” “Thursday,” “Friday,” and “Saturday.” The repeated panels visually emphasize daily brushing.\n\nBack in the restaurant, a younger adult man with dark hair, wearing a dark suit and light-colored tie, stands near the host. A blonde woman is partly visible at his side, smiling. The gray-haired host, still in his tuxedo with boutonniere, looks down at something in his hand, then turns toward the man. The younger man smiles broadly, speaking to the host, while the host listens with a composed, slightly puzzled expression. The two men face each other closely in the softly lit dining room, with other guests and dark wall panels behind them.\n\nThe host leans in and gestures with one hand, pointing slightly as if clarifying a seating choice. The younger man continues smiling, then his expression shifts to surprise as he looks toward the host. He opens his mouth as if correcting him, then begins to move away to the left. The host remains in place, watching after him. His face changes from confident to taken aback, his eyes widening a little as he looks off to the side, as though reconsidering what he assumed.\n\nThe final image is a clean product display on a white surface. Three Topol toothpaste packages are arranged in a small arc: two boxes in front and one raised behind them. The front-left box has the red “Topol” logo; the front-right box has a green “Topol” logo and a green end marked “GEL.” The rear box also shows the Topol name with orange-red graphic accents. Centered below the boxes in bold black text is the slogan: “The only toothpaste a smoker needs.”",
